# Testing Conventions

- Tests mirror `src/mdpp/` layout: `tests/analysis/`, `tests/plots/`.
- Shared fixtures live in `tests/conftest.py` (e.g. `two_atom_trajectory`, `correlated_ca_trajectory`).
- Test functions are named `test_<function>_<behavior>`.
- Use `pytest.approx` for floating-point comparisons.
- Plotting tests use `matplotlib.use("Agg")` and call `plt.close(figure)` after assertions.
- Import from public API paths (`from mdpp.analysis.metrics import compute_rmsd`).
- No `__init__.py` files in test directories (pytest discovers without them).

## Pytest Markers

Three custom markers (registered in `pyproject.toml`, `--strict-markers` enforced):

| Marker | Use when |
|---|---|
| `@pytest.mark.benchmark` | The test reports timing/throughput (typically with printed output) |
| `@pytest.mark.slow` | The test takes >10 s wall time |
| `@pytest.mark.gpu` | The test exercises cupy/torch/jax backends |

Combine freely: `@pytest.mark.benchmark` + `@pytest.mark.slow` + `@pytest.mark.gpu` on a large-scale GPU benchmark.

Users run:

- `pytest -m "not gpu"` -- CPU-only environments
- `pytest -m "not benchmark"` -- fast CI (correctness only)
- `pytest -m "benchmark and not slow"` -- fast perf checks
